columns.text:
The net present value of a project is a good indicator of how profitable an investment is. It measures the present value of your investment at a certain time and at a certain required rate of return. The general formula for this is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=(\text{Annual cash flow} \times \text{Present value of cash})-\text{Project cost}
\end{aligned}$$

Next, we need to solve for the value of the internal rate of return that will make the company indifferent between accepting and rejecting it. To do this, we will equate the NPV as zero and use this formula for the present value annuity factor:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value annuity factor}&=\dfrac{1-(1+r)^{-\text{Duration}}}{r}
\end{aligned}$$

Where $r$ is the rate.

Isolating the part of the equation with the unknown variable on one side, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\$63,000}{\$11,700}&=\dfrac{1-(1+r)^{-9}}{r}\\[15 pt]
5.38462&=\dfrac{1-(1+r)^{-9}}{r}
\end{aligned}$$

Cross multiply to remove the denominator:

$$\begin{aligned}
5.38462r&=1-(1+r)^{-9}
\end{aligned}$$

Once again, isolate the unknown variable:

$$\begin{aligned}
5.38462r-1&=(1+r)^{-9}
\end{aligned}$$

Plotting this in an equation solver, we can get $r$ or the internal rate of return that will make the company indifferent as $11.724\%$.
